    <lineage>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>We mapped kinematic elements based on the position and geometry of strike-slip faults and on the overall distribution of bedrock, talus, and drainages visible in lidar data. The lidar data were acquired by the Alaska Division of Geological and Geophysical Surveys (DGGS) on June 26, 2020.  A shaded-relief image of the lidar are included in this release, but the LiDAR data are not part of this data release. The lidar data will be released by DGGS in 2021. Kinematic element boundaries are approximately located and are a result of cumulative, differential patterns and amounts of movement that began at inception of the landslides. Elements and/or their boundaries may change location as the landslides continue to evolve. Kinematic elements mapped in 2020 may or may not reflect patterns of historical short-term, episodic movement, or patterns of movement in the future.</procdesc>
